<<button "I know what you mean">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-06">><</button>>

<<button "That’s not how I see it">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-06">><</button>>
</div>

</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-06 {"position":"454,323","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-06">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-07">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_06" play>><<set $map1 = setup.generateDirectionsMapWP([51.51029183629383, -0.08606857296172754],[51.51035944551418, -0.0871975864519973], "London Bridge")>>
<main>Yeah well.

I can’t imagine what the city looked like before the fire.

All the buildings and monuments that say London to me were built straight after. Like this one.

But sure there was a city before that, when London Bridge had houses
and shops on it, and one before that: Londinium. What would I recognise of that if I had a time machine?

Anyway, we’d better get moving. I’ll be late for work.

With the church of St Magnus the Martyr (another of Wren’s) on my
left, I walk away from the Monument on Monument Street, not taking my
life into my own hands with the traffic of King William Street but diligently walking over to the pedestrian crossing.

Once across, I go left and then take a sharp right onto Arthur Street, which is almost a circle. 

$map1

<<button "At Arthur Street">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-07">><</button>>
     

</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-07 {"position":"455,445","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-07">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-08">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_07" play>><<set $map2 = setup.generateDirectionsMap([51.51035944551418, -0.0871975864519973], [51.51116071917635, -0.08949355746559208])>>
<main>$map2

Another right onto Martin Lane then pass under the streetlamp to Laurence Pountney Hill. 

St Laurence Poutney was once a church but it was destroyed in the Great Fire and this one they didn’t rebuild. All that’s left is the name.

I prefer to take the quiet route so I have a bit of time alone with my thoughts. 

I was in Turkey on a dig when I heard the news. In Antalya. The Temple of Apollo. I got the first flight home but I couldn’t stay there. 

Part of me felt like going back out to Turkey after that, or somewhere else, somewhere even further. There were projects in Mexico, Cambodia. But that felt childish, somehow. I’m almost 30, I thought, I can’t run away. But I can’t be back there either.

So I ended up here. Seemed like a sensible sort of decision. A grownup job. A boring sensible job for a property developer in the City of London.

Oh we’ll go straight onto Gophir Lane, here. I always think of a little animal when I pass along it. I’ve never looked up the origin of the name because I don’t want to shatter that illusion.

Then a right on Bush Lane.

<<button "At Bush Lane">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-08">><</button>>
     

</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-08 {"position":"455,560","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-08">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-09">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_08" play>><<set $map3 = setup.generateDirectionsMap([51.51116071917635, -0.08949355746559208], [51.51242937363779, -0.08875326774174161])>><main>$map3

I say it’s boring. I mean it often is but every now and then you’ll discover something pretty amazing.

Stop me if you’re finding this too dull but here’s how it works. I do one or two surveys for any site where the company’s seeking planning permission. The first is a survey I’ll do at my desk: the dullest part. It’s historical research to check if there’s any reason to believe that the site could have historically significant items buried that we’d either be covering up or damaging by building there.

Carefully cross Cannon Street here to St Swithins Lane. Look out for traffic.

We’ll keep on down St Swithins Lane for a bit, when we’re over.


<<button "Across">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-09">><</button>>
     




</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-09 {"position":"458,683","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-09">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-10">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_09" play>><<set $map4 = setup.generateDirectionsMap([51.51242937363779, -0.08875326774174161], [51.512755942991646, -0.08907766602607836])>>
<main>$map4

Depending on the location of the site, I’ll make a recommendation based on what I know and what I can discover of its history.

If it’s the middle of nowhere, the chances of historical significance are slimmer. It’s all about weighing up probabilities. When a site comes up for development in the City of London though, you can pretty much guarantee that I’ll make a recommendation to move onto a second survey, which involves me being on-site. A proper archaeological investigation.

That’s because there’s always something historically significant here. And if the Victorians built something, you can be sure they weren’t particularly rigorous about checking what was lying beneath.

That’s exactly what happened with the girl.

Left here on Mansion House Place.


<<button "At Mansion House Place">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-10">><</button>>
     




</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-10 {"position":"456,808","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-10">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-11A">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_10" play>><<set $map5 = setup.generateDirectionsMap([51.512755942991646, -0.08907766602607836], [51.51278944399552, -0.09011492250314354])>>
<main>$map5

When the IRA bombed the Baltic Exchange and they - English Heritage, this was, not the IRA realised fully restoring it would be too expensive, the land was bought for development. And that’s where I came in. I knew it was very likely I’d find some artefacts, probably Roman, but I wasn’t prepared for finding her.

Take St Stephens Row to Walbrook. That’s the name of one of one of the old London rivers, buried underground now.


<<button "At Walbrook">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-11A">><</button>>
     

</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-11A {"position":"450,925","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-11A">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-12">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_11A" play>>
<main>

When you see Bank tube station, go across. Just to the left of it, push the glass door and go inside. Take a look around.

Okay I have to be honest. This isn’t actually where I work. It’s a few doors down but I like to come here sometimes. Underneath, there’s a whole Roman Mithraeum. Not many people know about it. Geeky archaeology insider tip.

Are you inside now? Let me know when you are.

<<button "I'm inside now">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-12">><</button>>
     




</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-12 {"position":"458.33333333333337,1051.6666666666667","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-12">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-13">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_12" play>>
<main>

Maybe one day the Mithraeum will be open to the public. I’ve been taken down there before and it’s incredible. Mithras was a Cult, in the Roman sense. That word didn’t hold negative connotations for the most part at the time but these guys actually were kinda culty. There’s a lot we don’t know about it but it looks like a kind of Romanisation of Zoroastrianism. Or maybe just a way of people continuing the worship the old gods without seeming like bad Romans. We’re a long way from Persia here though so it must have been popular.

Oh and in case you didn’t know, fire’s a big part of Zoroastrianism. Mad for the fire, they were.

<<timed 10s>><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "RP-13">><</timed>>
     




</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: RP-13 {"position":"458.33333333333337,1176.6666666666667","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "RP-13">><<set $nextpassage to "RP-14">><<audio ":all" stop>><<audio "RP_13" play>>
<main>
Mithras, my master. I have come to you in my hour of despair 

My beloved has perished

For three years I was away from her. I wanted to prove myself a warrior. Show her family that my strength could compensate for my common blood. That I would bring honour to Rome.

I left the comforts of Londinium and joined the army in Caledonia but the Northern Barbarians overwhelmed us. And the weather. I’ve never been known so much rain. Every day was a battle to exist.

When we retreated and returned to Camulodunum, I didn’t know what to
do. I couldn’t return to Londinium boasting of our victories, like I’d planned. There had been no victory.

Defeat at the hands of barbarians could only bring shame on Rome.

So I remained in Camulodunum. I asked for guidance, O wise Mithras, but none came.

I do not mean to criticise.

Am I being tested? Why did she have to die?

After everything I did for her.

She left me like this.

And I am lost.

Mithras. I beg of you. Send me a sign.

