<main>$map6

Knowing a place is knowing its back streets.

A lot like knowing a person.

Straight across to Watling Street then. The ancient roman road that meets the Devil’s Highway.

Did the people of Londinium walk around at lunchtime gassing about their work colleagues, y’think?

Sure their lunchbreaks would have been six hours long, they were hardly grabbing a sandwich.

I know you were older than her as well but her shape is how I remember you. When I’d come home for Christmas and you’d beg me to let you come to the Gweedore with me. And I’d try saying no but you knew I’d relent and I’d spend the whole night running after you every time you’d disappear.

The Romans always buried their dead outside the walls of the City, to the North East mostly, so her being found within the city limits suggests importance. Maybe her family were just rich.

I don’t blame anyone. I tried that young lad Stephen. He was devastated, I know. I don’t think he believed me. I never looked for anyone to blame. I hope he’s okay. I wish I’d met him before. Like I’d seen you two together, being happy, being young. Together.

Let’s not go too far down here.
